bug.short_desc: [Cell Editors] - Cell Editor action handler doesn't handle dynamic undo text

long_desc.thetext:
The CellEditorActionHandler allows clients to install an undo and redo handler that should be used when the cell editor is not open. However, there is no support for the fact that most undo and redo handlers update their action text according to the operation to be undone/redone. Further, the enablement conditions on undo and redo action handlers change dynamically.
CellEditorActionHandlers need to monitor property change events of their underlying undo/redo actions and update the enablement and text accordingly.
This is required so that the task views, bookmark views, etc. show the correct text in the undo/redo actions when there is a marker operation to be undone.
I'll fix this as part of working on support for undoing workspace operations, target milestone M2.
Fixed in HEAD, >20060822

verified on WinXP, I20060919-0010. In the task list: - when the cell editor is open, undo is enabled for the text editing actions in the cell - when the cell editor is not open, the undo for the latest task op (such as "Undo Add Task") is available, and it is disabled if there is none available. It also correctly responds to changes in the undo history.

bug.short_desc: [Wizards] WizardDialog.run() has unexpected results if invoked from FocusOut

long_desc.thetext:
If WizardDialog.run() is invoked from a FocusOut listener it will have undesirable effects. If FocusOut fires as a result of selecting another widget the focus will be set back to the widget that lost focus once the runnable is ran. If the focus is lost via traversal it will create a loop that will only end once a control that doesn't raise focus events receives focus.
Attaching snippet and some logs to help explain.
Created an attachment (id=48207) snippet

Created an attachment (id=48208) traversal log
This log file shows what occurs on traversal from a Text that invokes run on FocusOut.
Notes about the log: * The numbers at the beginning of the line are the System.identityHashCode() of the object throwing the event or be acted upon. * The event types are SWT event types (31=Traversal, 16=FocusOut, 15=FocusIn). * The "WizardDialog get focus control" and "WizardDialog set focus control" are logged when the WizardDialog stores and sets the focus control. * "setEnabled(*)" is from Control.setEnabled() * "run..." is the runnable being invoked
(It's a little dense but it worked)
One of the main problems is that the WizardDialog retrieves the focus control before running the process which will be the control that is currently throwing the FocusOut event. This control then gets focus after the runnable is ran. You can also see that during this loop FocusOut is thrown from other controls as they're disabled. It appears that the operating system is still processing the traverse event hence the looping that doesn't stop until a control receives focus that doesn't provide focus events.

Created an attachment (id=48209) lost focus on selection log
This log has the same data as the other except that it was created by selected another widget rather than using traversal. You can see that it starts with focus in a Text and once the runnable is ran the focus is set back to that same Text.

Created an attachment (id=48210) exported breakpoints that log events
If this helps these conditional breakpoints are what I used to log the events to track down what was occurring. Also the issues occur in both 3.2 and 3.3M1. The breakpoints are from the 3.3M1 distribution (line numbers might matter, not sure).
Brad, what would you expect to happen? I don't think we can detect that there is a FocusOut event being processed. I guess a workaround for you would be to use an asyncExec.

(In reply to comment #5) > Brad, what would you expect to happen?
The ideal would be that the runnable is invoked once and focus goes to the control that is to receive focus, not the one that it's leaving. But if the ideal can't be achieved I would expect the runnable to only run once. Currently if focus is lost because of traversal the runnable is invoked multiple times until a control is found that can receive focus. In the use case of the user selecting another control focus will always get set back to the control that is running a runnable on FocusOut thus locking the user into the Control.
> I don't think we can detect that there > is a FocusOut event being processed. I guess a workaround for you would be to > use an asyncExec.
There is one way other than asyncExec but it involves a Display filter. Basically when a FocusOut is fired the filter sets a flag and then in run() this flag is checked. I have some code written that does this and then sets focus to the appropriate control after the runnable is invoked. But I may have run into a scenario that I can't work around, I'm not sure yet. If you want me to go into more detail I can.
I think we'd run into other issues if done from the asyncExec. The reason that validation is being performed on FocusOut is that on Verify or Modify it would be too expensive. The result of the validation could disable other Controls and we're trying to prevent the user from performing a selection that could leave the UI in an inconsistent state. If done from an asyncExec the selection of another control would be invoked before validation.

My read of the javadoc for run(...) is that it is performing as specified, at least the case where you select another widget. It states that UI state is saved before executing the runnable and that any changes to UI state during the runnable are ignored. Since you are running this on the focus out event, all of the UI gets disabled, the UI state (including focus control) is saved, and all is restored when the runnable is done. Hence the focus going back to the original widget that had it.
The traversal behavior sounds bogus and I have not looked into that one more closely since I don't think you should be using run(...) on FocusOut for the reasons stated above.
It sounds as if you want synchronous validation on FocusOut to prevent the user from putting the UI in an inconsistent state, and that you don't want a disabled UI. So I'm not sure why you are using the run(...) method, which disables the UI and recommends forked execution. Have you tried doing the validation synchronously on FocusOut?
Since this is an issue in WizardDialog, moving to Karice, but I'll continue to participate in the discussion...

I guess I come at this from a different angle. The API for IRunnableContext talks about running a runnable in the context of the implementor and that's what I'm attempting to do. But the WizardDialog implementation isn't allowing for that in specific use cases even if I specify to not fork and run synchronously. I might be splitting hairs but for me this is where the disconnect is.

I guess I want to figure out how to get you your FocusOut validation without using WizardDialog.run(). I don't have a lot of experience with this method, I'm just reading the javadoc, which says that running with fork true is "recommended" and that if you don't fork you have to run your own event loop. And it says that the UI will be locked and any attempt to change the UI in the runnable will be "nullified."
So given all those caveats, it seems like the wrong method to be using for synchronous UI validation that is going to make UI calls. So my question is...what is not working by just responding to FocusOut directly?

(In reply to comment #9) > So given all those caveats, it seems like the wrong method to be using for > synchronous UI validation that is going to make UI calls. So my question > is...what is not working by just responding to FocusOut directly?
Responding to FocusOut directly works just fine.
Brad - Is this bug resolved now that Bug 155164 is resolved?

(In reply to comment #11) > Brad - Is this bug resolved now that Bug 155164 is resolved? >
No and it's a little tricky why not. I'll try to get my head completely around it when I can find the time but SWT is still attempting to process the traversal event thus it keeps visiting each control, in the traversal case that is.

bug.short_desc: [hashcode/equals] running twice produces incorrect call to super

long_desc.thetext: The check for obj == null is also missing!

The reason that the check for null is missing is that when the code generator runs, it checks to see if there's an implementation already in the hierarchy above. The first code is the template for 'there is no superclass implementation' whilst the second code is the template for 'there is a superclass implementation'. You don't need to check null at each stage, since the superclass will check it for you.
Of course, this is a bug, and the (re)generation of the equals method shouldn't be thinking that there is an implementation of the superclass at all when regenerating the equals method; but that appears to be what it is doing.

Hello,
Some search results are shown corrupted for Russian (see screencapture). To reproduce: 1) Start eclipse with 20060816-nl2-win32.zip as "eclipse -nl ru" 2) Select Help > Help Contents. 3) Enter "xml" as a search word and click GO button. 4) See the result list.

Created an attachment (id=48216) search.gif
<cde:tctdetail> Testcase: Project: WSW32 Component: CDE - Platform/UI Priority: 1 Subject: DVT: RUS Corruption in the search results Article ID: 1022 Originator: aglotov@trans.msu.su </cde:tctdetail>
Could this be Lucene?

I couldn't find the 20060816 language packs, only the latest ones (20060822), but the org.eclipse.platform.doc.user.nl2_3.2.0.v200606220026.jar appears to have no doc content. Can you either send me a sample plugin that doesn't work, or tell me how to get a build that has russian doc content?

I found the problem - it is a limitation of the lucene HTML parser that is used to index documents. The parser will attempt to detect the encoding of the document by grabbing the first 2048 bytes and looking for the meta that specifies the encoding. The reason it only does the first bit is for performance and complexity; it has to cope with broken HTML and be as fast as possible. The problem is that the meta tag that specifies the encoding is after the first 2048 bytes and it just doesn't find it.
While technically the document validates as proper HTML, it could be considered bad practice to place encoded content before the meta tag that specifies the encoding.

--------
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN"><HTML> <HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=UTF-8"> <meta name="copyright" content="Copyright (c) IBM Corporation (...russian...) 2000, 2006. (...russian...)" > <META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css"> ...

bug.short_desc: thisJoinPoint.getSignature().getMethod() returns NULL in a call join point

long_desc.thetext: Created an attachment (id=48219) test case

null is returned because we use 'getDeclaredMethod()' in the implementation of:
Method method = methodSignature.getMethod();
the mayPerform() method isnt declared in the AuthorizationAdmin interface and so getDeclaredMethod() returns null. The javadoc around getMethod() isn't very complete - not describing if it should behave like getMethod() or getDeclaredMethod(). Obviously the former is implied from the name but when I change it then some tests fail that are relying on the behaviour of the latter!
I suspect we just want to return whatever we can find ... finding it by any means.
I had to implement a similar "find the matching method declaration in the hierarchy" strategy for the Spring AOP integration with AspectJ. We should be able to reuse the algorithm here...
So you needed an algorithm more than: call getDeclaredMethod() - if it returned null then trying getMethod()?

Let me engage brain a little more clearly here... ;)
Firstly, the intent of "getMethod" is to return a java.lang.Method object that represents the method being called at the join point. Since it is part of the Signature, we are after the static "subject" (to use our AJ 5 Dev Notebook terminology) of the join point. This certainly includes non-public methods, so it is not the same as Class.getMethod(s) for example.
Class.getDeclaredMethod() however only returns methods directly declared in the type in question. Here we need to try getDeclaredMethod, and if that returns null start walking up the parent types calling getDeclaredMethod until we find a match...
I've also written code that walks the inheritance hierarchy looking for declared methods. That's surely what's needed here.

Surprisingly, the same technique _works_ with inherited fields! You can get field-signatures with this code:
FieldSignature fs = (FieldSignature)thisjoinpoint.getSignature(); Field f = fs.getField();
Why does it work with fields and not with methods?
As a workauround I am using a recursive method that goes up the hierarchy-tree until it reaches Object.class. But I don't want to search the hole tree in every advice invocation.
Glck Auf Timo
i believe the code is implemented for field walking already but not for method walking - that is why it works for fields.

bug.short_desc: A Period in a schema file name is not mapped to a package name

long_desc.thetext:
EMF maps periods in schema file names incorrectly. For example "Stops.Not.Liked.1.2.xsd" becomes the package name "StopsNotLiked12" and file name "StopsNotLiked12.ecore".
Please correct this so it would produce "Stops.Not.Liked.1.2" for the package, and "Stops.Not.Liked.1.2.ecore" for the ecore file.
XSD version: 2.1.0.v200606271057

Matthew,
Generally the package name is determined from the namespace, not the file name, except for null target namespace schemas. Changing the default mangling rules for how a package name is derived from a namespace URI (or from the schema's location URI for null target namespace schemas) will break people relying on what the rules currently do and those people would then be forced to add an ecore:package annotation to get the behavior they are getting now. So the best approach here is for you to use an ecore:package annotation to choose exactly the package name you want. The import wizard also allows you to edit the name of the .ecore file if the default is not to your liking; just click on it to active the cell editor to edit it. A subsequent "Reload..." of the model will preserve the file name choice and of course the annotation will always be respected as well.
The thinking here was that "/" separates the segments of a compound name but that "." is used to build a single long name. That's certainly the necessary interperation when dealing with names of complex types, for example, which are NCNames that can contain a "." but not a "/" and must be mapped to a single valid Java identifier. The same mangling rules for NCNames are applied to the segments of the URI.
So the bottom line is that you can achieve the result you want (the ability to choose any package name and any Ecore resource name) without EMF needing to change the default rules. And as I said, while changing the rules might please one client, it will not please others who will likely consider such a change in behavior a bug.

It immediately goes into the "Republish" state after a successful publish. It was in the "Synchronized" state for half a second right after the publish finished.
If you want to test with my code you can grab everything from here: https://wagenknecht.org/svn/public/opensource/eclipse/gwt/trunk/
The publish operation is defined in the org.eclipseguru.gwt.core plug-in: https://wagenknecht.org/svn/public/opensource/eclipse/gwt/trunk/plugins/org.eclipseguru.gwt.core/src/org/eclipseguru/gwt/core/server/GwtProjectServerPublishOperation.java
The org.eclipseguru.gwt.ui plug-in contributes the launchable client.
You should get to that point following this screencast: http://eclipseguru.org/screencasts/gwt-tooling-intro/

The republish/synchronized state is based on the resources in the project and what was published to the server. The basic issue appears to be that on the first publish the server takes a snapshot of the files in the workspace, then triggers your task and publishes. Once the publish is done it notices that you've changed some files in the module and kicks off an autopublish.
Tomcat servers have autopublish enabled by default and you can turn that off, but that isn't going to solve the problem since the server already thinks it is out of sync.
The first part of the solution is making sure that your task is incremental, or more importantly that it doesn't rerun if it isn't going to change anything (e.g. it shouldn't run if no resources have changed since the last time it ran or if the changes are already made). This will reduce the infinite publishing to just two publish operations.
The remaining issue is making sure that the changes you made are included in the original publish operation instead of requiring a second publish. Is your task only operating on modules that already have changes in a publish operation (e.g. only runs the first time a module is added to a server or only in reaction to changes to files within a module, like codegen)?
If not, then I'm not sure how we can solve this in 1.5.x. If yes, then there should be a way to include the new files in the delta that's already being published. Can you try adding the following two lines at the end of your task after it has made the changes? It may help to clear the publishing cache and pick up your changes in the first publish.
((Server)server).getServerPublishInfo().clearCache(); ((Server)server).getServerPublishInfo().startCaching();
Tim, this looks similar to 152146 for which I am currently investigating.

bug.short_desc: Support camelcase navigation on PDE forms

long_desc.thetext:
Support camelcase-style navigation on PDE forms, eg:
On a extension field of type class, if the value is "com.mycompany.myclass.FooBar", the Ctrl+Left/Right would move the cursor to the following positions (marked with "|"):
"com|.|mycompany|.|myclass|.|Foo|Bar"
A similar behavior can be observed on "Open Type" dialog (Ctrl+Shift+T).
This feature would be useful at first on class fields, but I think ID or path-like fields would take advantage of this too, once they usually use a full-qualified-classname-like pattern.

bug.short_desc: WST code assumes IResource.getLocation() returns a non-null value

long_desc.thetext:
In a couple of places
org.eclipse.wst.sse.core.internal.model.ModelManagerImpl.calculateURIResolver org.eclipse.wst.sse.core.internal.FileBufferModelManager.createURIResolver org.eclipse.wst.xml.core.internal.validation.core.AbstractNestedValidator.validate
in the wst.sse and wst.xml code, when creating a URIResolver the code calls
IResource.getLocation() but does not check the returned value for null.
With the introduction of EFS in Eclipse 3.2, IResource.getLocation will return null if the resource is a link to a resource in another IFileSystem (e.g. a file on a FTP server if the org.eclipse.core.filesystem.ftp prototype plugin is in use.) The above code results in NullPointerExceptions, causing any SSE based editors (e.g. the XML or WSDL editors) to throw NullPointers when opening a linked resource. This is causing us some problems as we rely on the WTP editors handling linked resources.
To reproduce: 1) Install plugins for an alternative IFileSystem implementation - see http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/EFS 2) Put some sample files (html & wsdl) into your filesytem backend (e.g. onto the FTP server if using the FTP plugin) 3) Create an empty simple project. 4) Edit the .project file and linkedResource entries: <linkedResources> <link> <name>index.html</name> <type>1</type> <locationURI>ftp//localhost/index.html</locationURI> </link> <link> <name>hello.wsdl</name> <type>1</type> <locationURI>ftp://localhost/hello.wsdl</locationURI> </link> </linkedResources> 5) Try opening the linked file int the workspace and then check the ErrorLog.
Note: You make need to pick up the patch mentioned at https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=137878 if you want to use the FTP plugin. (I'm testing using a HTTP IFileSystem impl that I am writing).
See http://help.eclipse.org/help32/index.jsp?topic=/org.eclipse.platform.doc.isv/porting/3.2/incompatibilities.html for more documentation ont the change of behavior in E3.2.
In some places switching to IResource.getLocationURI() might be appropriate - I'm not sure as the expected value of URIResolver#fileBaseLocation is not javadoc'ed.
FileBufferModelManager.createURIResolver() probably needs rework as it seems to have a special case for resources in the workspace (which might now be links to external resources).

I've reveiwed the steps I outlined below to double check them and actually found that the FTP file sytem implementation isn't the most reliable to use (especially with a Windows XP FTP server). Aplogies for that, I didn't realise as I was testing using a lightweight HTTP based EFS file system plugin*. I'm attaching a build of this HTTP IFilesystem plugin that may help simplify your reproducing this problem.
To reiterate, the problem is primarily that WTP XML/SSE editors cannot sucessfully open an XML IResource that is actually a workspace link to a URI that is resolved by a non-local EFS IFileSystem implementation.
To reproduce: 1) Install the attached com.capeclear.filesystem.http plugin in your eclipse runtime 2) Place the attached .wsdl and .xml files onto a local web server (e.g. local apache or tomcat server). The default root URL (assumed by the project below) is http://localhost:8000/) 3) Fire up Eclipse and import the attached testlink project. 4) If your HTTP server is not at the above URL, edit the .project file and change each <locationURI> element to point to the correct location for each resource. 5) In the Navigator view, try opening the linked files. 2) There seems to be quite a lot of URIResolver related code that assumes that XML/WSDL <import> element "location" attributes only contain URLs that can ultimately be resolved to a path on the local file system. This assumption is invalid - import locations can be any valid URL (e.g. http://) as i the examples above.
I'm attaching a number of example patches for various classes in WST SSE and WST XML that I've had to modify in order to get rid of the NullPointerExceptions while simply loading linked resources.
I'm afraid I'm not certain that these patches don't break other pieces of the editors (specifically the URI Resolver code) so I don't think they are suitable as-is. Those more familiar with the SSE/XML code would know better.

For the moment you can assume that the implementation will happily attempt to load any HTTP:// resource you point it at (from any HTTP 1.0 compliant server)

long_desc.thetext:

Step: 1.New sample datasource named sampleDB 2.New a dataset named CUSTOMERS 3.select * from CLASSICMODELS.CUSTOMERS 4.Insert a data item and binding@to CUSTOMERS 5.Add a data binding column and New data Item dialog pop up. 6.Without rename the Name. 7.Select Any 8.Open expression Editor, select Available Data Sets, select CUSTOMERS, select column of "CUSTOMERNUMBER" and click OK 9.Without click Enable binding with the same expression. 10.Click OK.
Actual result: The data binding column has been not added in binding list.
Exception reuslt: The data binding column is added in binding list.

in what case user should check "Enable binding with the same expression"? and in what cases user should not check this option?
Can we make a choice and do not expose this option? for example, always allow user to have the same expression for different column bindinds? as long as the column name is different, can we need user to decide or check if the expression is same as another column binding?

By default if user creats an new binding with same expression, we'll use the previous one. The issue is at creating stage, it's difficult to let user check if the binding column, which has same expression, is exiting or not. If we always creats new binding column, the amount can be very big. I think in most cases use the previous one is reasonable except user check the option to create a new one explicit.

+1 if the new binding column name and expression are the same as an existing one, we can always reuse the existing one.
+1 also to resuse an existing binding column if user specify an expression but did not specify the new binding column name.
The case that not quite clear is when user specify an expression AND a new column name, how do we let user reuse an existing binding column? Does the new column name replace the existing column name or we ignore the new column name?
I think for case (1) and (2), we do not need to show the "Enable binding with the same expression" option, and simply reuse the existing data binding column. For case (3), we always create a new binding column.
in summary, I think it will be a simpler UI not to have this option.

For case 3 we ignore the new column name. Currently, we generate an unique column name when user try to add one. How can user find if another column, which has the same expression, become the problem. For current design, it's not easy to that. We try to provide this option to user, so that he/she can force to create an new column whenver he/she knows an same expression column existing.

how about following this steps: 1. if user DnD a data set column from data explorer, try to reuse an existing data binding on that data set column. (case 1) 2. if user DnD a new data item fro pallete, try to reuse a binding if the new data item has the same name and expression as an existing one (case 2), if the data item name user gave is different from any existing one, create a new one. (case 3) 3. If user click on "new" in property editor's data binding tab, always create a new one, regardless if there is an existing expressions. If the name user entered has been used by another data binding, prompt the user that the name has been used, give user the oppotunity to rename or cancel the creation.
I'm OK for this. Chao, could you please review this and change accordingly if every looks fine to you?

We think that there has two different binding behaviours between the designer editor and the property editor.If user want to create new binding with the same expression,he or she has to use property editor to do so.
Verified and closed
